## 3. Guide for Future Code Modifications

Here is exactly how to implement your proposed changes.

### A. Modifying the Reward Function (e.g., Minimizing Number of Vehicles)
Currently, [reward_func](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/VRP/vrp_utils.py#253-290) only penalizes the Euclidean distance. To make the model minimize the number of vehicles, you must penalize it every time it visits the depot.
* **Where to change:** [VRP/vrp_utils.py](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/VRP/vrp_utils.py) inside [reward_func(sample_solution)](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/VRP/vrp_utils.py#253-290).
* **How to change:** The `sample_solution` contains the sequence of nodes visited. You can count how many times the Depot node (index `n_nodes - 1`) appears in the sequence (excluding the automatic end-of-route return).
* **Code concept:**
  ```python
  # Add a penalty for depot visits
  depot_visists = tf.reduce_sum(tf.cast(tf.equal(sample_idxs, env.n_nodes - 1), tf.float32), axis=0)
  vehicle_penalty = depot_visits * vehicle_penalty_weight
  route_lens_decoded = route_lens_decoded + vehicle_penalty
  ```
  *(Note: You will need to pass `sample_idxs` directly into the reward function or extract it from the environment state tracking).*

### B. Ensuring All Customer Nodes are Visited
The model sometimes fails to route to some nodes because the decoding loop terminates prematurely or the mask allows early termination.
* **Where to change:** First, [main.py](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/main.py) / [configs.py](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/configs.py). The `decode_len` hyperparameter determines how many steps the decoder takes. If `decode_len` is too short, testing will stop before all demand is fulfilled. Increase `--decode_len` (e.g., from 40 to 60 for VRP20).
* **Where to change:** [VRP/vrp_utils.py](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/VRP/vrp_utils.py) inside `Env.step()`. Ensure that the Depot is heavily masked (disallowed) if the total remaining demand is > 0, EXCEPT when the vehicle load is exactly 0 (it must restock). Currently, the mask is:
  ```python
  self.mask += tf.concat( [tf.tile(tf.expand_dims(tf.cast(tf.equal(self.load,0), tf.float32),1), [1,self.n_cust]),                      
      tf.expand_dims(tf.multiply(tf.cast(tf.greater(tf.reduce_sum(self.demand,1),0),tf.float32),
                       tf.squeeze( tf.cast(tf.equal(idx,self.n_cust),tf.float32))),1)],1)
  ```
  Make sure this logic correctly forcefully zeroes out the probability of selecting the depot if `demand` > 0 and [load](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/model/attention_agent.py#321-325) > 0. If the problem persists, you can artificially inject a massive negative reward (penalty) in [reward_func](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/VRP/vrp_utils.py#253-290) if `tf.reduce_sum(env.demand)` at the end of the episode is strictly greater than 0.

### C. Improving the Optimization Model
If you want to move beyond basic Sequence-to-Sequence + Attention, you have a few powerful avenues in the codebase:
1. **Try Advanced RL Algorithms:** The codebase supports multiple algorithms. Try `python main.py --rl_model ppo` instead of the default `reinforce`. Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) generally provides vastly superior and more stable optimization paths, allowing larger batch sizes and multiple epochs over the same rollout data.
2. **Transformer Encoders:** Currently, the Encoder ([shared/embeddings.py](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/shared/embeddings.py)) just linearly projects the `x,y` features. You can modify [attention_agent.py](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/model/attention_agent.py) to pass the embeddings through a stack of Transformer layers (Multi-Head Self-Attention). This allows the nodes to "talk to each other" before the decoding step begins, achieving much higher spatial awareness.
3. **Graph Neural Networks (GNNs):** You can build a Graph Convolutional Network (GCN) step inside the Actor ([model/attention_agent.py](file:///c:/COLLEGE/SEM%20X/WORK/VRP-RL_2018/model/attention_agent.py)). Nodes can pass messages to their K-nearest neighbors based on spatial distances, vastly improving the context representation passed into `decoder_input`.
